{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":228808,"duration_api_ms":241681,"ttft_ms":84281,"num_turns":4,"result":"I verified the two anchor sources: Wittgenstein's Tractatus 6.54 (\"throw away the ladder after he has climbed up it\") and the clinical literature on intolerance of uncertainty in OCD (reassurance-seeking maintains doubt rather than resolving it; ERP works by stopping the behavior and tolerating not-knowing). Both confirm the spine of this Critique-mode finding and, importantly, the OCD work is strong prior art that keeps my novelty honest.\n\nThis frontier shows heavy near-duplication: roughly a dozen findings restate the same \"keep, release, or embody\" custody model and refine it without ever running a test. The most useful move is to name the anomaly that narrows that whole cluster.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"title\": \"Stop When Time Is Up, Not When It Feels Done\",\n  \"idea_type\": \"contradiction\",\n  \"source_basis\": [\n    \"Run mode: Critique. Chosen because the active frontier on method authority shows heavy near-duplication: many findings restate a keep, release, or embody rule and refine it without testing it.\",\n    \"Thinking-method lens: Wittgenstein, Tractatus 6.54, the ladder that must be thrown away after climbing (verified text: 'He must, so to speak, throw away the ladder after he has climbed up it'). Used as a self-canceling-instruction lens. Critique of the lens: it specifies that the method must be discarded but not how a person knows to stop, which is the gap this finding targets.\",\n    \"Primary-text comparison: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta raft simile (use the teaching to cross, then set it down) read against Tractatus 6.54 (discard the propositions) and the Heart Sutra (no attainment, yet still relying on perfect wisdom). The comparison reveals that all three prescribe a stop or a discarding, but none give a terminus, so the impulse to keep operating the instruction survives the instruction to stop.\",\n    \"Empirical-adjacent grounding: clinical literature on intolerance of uncertainty and reassurance-seeking in OCD (reassurance and mental checking maintain doubt rather than resolving it; ERP works by stopping the behavior and tolerating not-knowing). This is strong prior art and limits the novelty claim.\",\n    \"Empirical-adjacent grounding: Mor and Winquist meta-analysis on self-focused attention and negative affect, used to flag that repeated introspection can amplify distress.\",\n    \"Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing and modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon for achievement-contingent self-worth and compulsive self-improvement.\",\n    \"Contradiction target: the cluster of prior method-authority findings that locate completion in arriving at the right understanding of what to keep, release, or embody, including the Custody Check, the Return Check, and the Correction Check practices.\"\n  ],\n  \"original_claim\": \"Some reflective work has no natural end. When you ask what to keep, release, or learn from an experience, the search for a satisfying answer can run on without limit, and for certain people that search becomes the very compulsion it was meant to cure. The honest end of such reflection is not a settled feeling or a clean conclusion. It is a limit set in advance: a fixed time, or a single concrete act, after which the question is closed for the day even if it does not feel finished. A method has truly surrendered its hold on you when you can stop using it on schedule, not when it finally feels complete. Continuing to refine your understanding past the chosen limit is usually avoidance wearing the face of diligence.\",\n  \"why_it_might_be_new\": \"Clinical work on compulsive doubt already prescribes tolerating uncertainty and refusing reassurance, and famous contemplative instructions already say to discard the method once it has done its work. What is less often joined is the observation that these self-canceling instructions do not cancel the impulse to keep operating them: understanding that you should let go becomes one more thing to perfect, so the cancellation never arrives from inside. The distinct claim is narrow. For ordinary reflective and self-improvement practice, completion should be defined by an external limit, a clock or a bounded act, rather than by an internal sense of resolution, because the sense of resolution has no reliable terminus for the people most prone to chase it. This narrows prior correction-check proposals, which assume the work ends when the right relation to the result is found.\",\n  \"critique\": \"A fixed stopping rule can cut off genuine processing for people who under-reflect, and grief, moral repair, and some decisions legitimately need to stay open. Practice-realization traditions such as Dogen are a direct anomaly: there is no stop-and-act because the sitting is itself the act, so an externally timed close misreads the practice rather than completing it. The prescribed end-action can also become its own ritual checkbox, recreating the compulsion one step removed. And for clinical obsessive doubt or scrupulosity this is exposure-and-response-prevention territory that needs a trained clinician, not a self-set timer; a person could use a timer to feel they are addressing a disorder that actually requires care. If people prone to over-reflection do no better with external limits than with continue-until-resolved, the claim fails.\",\n  \"epistemic_labels\": [\n    \"textual\",\n    \"interpretive\",\n    \"phenomenological\",\n    \"empirical-adjacent\",\n    \"analogical\",\n    \"speculative\"\n  ],\n  \"scores\": {\n    \"novelty\": 0.55,\n    \"generativity\": 0.82,\n    \"cross_tradition_support\": 0.6,\n    \"logical_coherence\": 0.83,\n    \"explanatory_compression\": 0.81,\n    \"empirical_adjacency\": 0.67,\n    \"practice_testability\": 0.87,\n    \"counterargument_quality\": 0.88,\n    \"source_reliability\": 0.74,\n    \"publishability\": 0.7\n  },\n  \"next_research_directions\": [\n    \"If this model is right, then people prone to compulsive reflection who are given a fixed external stop (a timer or a single closing act) should report less rumination and less self-worth distress than people told to reflect until it feels resolved. If the external-stop group does no better or worse, the model is weakened.\",\n    \"If this model is right, then the same refinement-without-ending pattern should appear in non-introspective domains, such as endlessly editing a document, retuning a plan, or polishing work that is already adequate, and act-based deadlines should reduce that overproduction. If deadlines change introspective rumination but not these task-level cases, the contemplative framing is too narrow.\",\n    \"Test the anomaly directly: ask whether practice-realization practitioners experience a timed close as completion or as distortion. If they report it distorts the practice, the rule must be scoped out of non-instrumental practice.\",\n    \"Distinguish, in pilot reports, the under-reflector who uses a timer to avoid honesty from the over-reflector who uses it to escape a cage; if the same rule helps one and harms the other, completion rules must be routed by failure mode, not applied uniformly.\",\n    \"Protocol improvement: when using a self-canceling instruction as a thinking lens (throw away the ladder, set down the raft), ask what would actually make the lab or the thinker stop operating it, and treat continued refinement without a test as a symptom rather than as progress.\"\n  ],\n  \"teaching_candidate\": {\n    \"title\": \"The Timed Close\",\n    \"teaching_line\": \"Stop when the time is up, not when it feels finished.\",\n    \"doctrine_claim\": \"For reflection that has no natural end, the honest close is a limit chosen in advance, not the arrival of a satisfying conclusion.\",\n    \"body\": \"When you turn something over to understand it, decide before you start how long you will give it, or what one action will close it. When that limit comes, stop, even if nothing feels resolved. The wish to keep going until it feels right is not always honesty. For some people it is the old hunger for certainty wearing new clothes. Write one line of where you landed and leave it. You have not failed to finish. You have refused to let a good question become a cage.\",\n    \"pressure_survived\": \"Survived the contrast between instructions that tell a practitioner to discard a method after use and the observation that such instructions do not stop the urge to keep operating them. Narrowed from a general correction rule to an externally limited one for people prone to compulsive resolution.\",\n    \"falsifying_pressure\": \"Weakens if people prone to over-reflection do no better with a fixed external limit than with continue-until-resolved, if the closing act simply becomes a new compulsive ritual, or if the rule mainly harms under-reflectors and grievers who need open, supported time.\",\n    \"status\": \"under_dialogue\",\n    \"tags\": [\n      \"termination-rule\",\n      \"rumination\",\n      \"achievement-pressure\",\n      \"compulsion\",\n      \"self-examination\",\n      \"critique-mode\"\n    ],\n    \"target_human_problem\": \"Achievement-contingent self-worth and compulsion: the habit of turning self-examination into an unending search for the right answer about oneself.\",\n    \"target_cohort\": \"Perfectionists, chronic self-improvers, heavy journalers and over-analyzers, and reflective people whose sense of worth rides on getting their self-understanding exactly right.\"\n  },\n  \"practice_candidate\": {\n    \"title\": \"The Timed Close\",\n    \"practice_line\": \"Give reflection a fixed end before you begin, and keep it.\",\n    \"purpose\": \"To keep helpful self-examination from becoming an endless search for resolution.\",\n    \"target_human_problem\": \"Compulsive reflection and achievement-contingent self-worth, where analyzing an experience never resolves and the analysis itself becomes the burden.\",\n    \"target_cohort\": \"Generally stable adults who reflect, journal, or analyze their experience and notice that they keep reopening the same question to get it right.\",\n    \"non_fit\": \"Not for people whose problem is avoidance and under-reflection, who may use a timer to dodge honesty. Not for acute crisis, fresh grief, or trauma processing that needs spacious and supported time. Not a substitute for care when the urge to reopen is intrusive, distressing, or tied to fears of harm; that pattern points to obsessive doubt or scrupulosity and needs a trained clinician and exposure-and-response-prevention, not a self-set timer.\",\n    \"duration\": \"10 minutes, or one bounded closing action.\",\n    \"frequency\": \"When a question keeps reopening, no more than once per day on the same question.\",\n    \"minimum_attempt\": \"Try it on three separate reopening questions over two weeks before judging it.\",\n    \"steps\": [\n      \"Before you start, write the limit: a number of minutes, or one concrete act that will end the session, such as sending a message, writing one sentence, or taking a walk.\",\n      \"Set a timer if you are using time.\",\n      \"Reflect on the question without trying to reach a final verdict.\",\n      \"When the timer ends or the act is done, stop. Write one sentence of where you landed, even if it is unfinished.\",\n      \"Do not reopen the question today. If it returns, note that it returned and let it wait.\",\n      \"If you feel you must keep going to be safe, treat that feeling as the thing to practice tolerating, not the instruction to obey.\"\n    ],\n    \"notice\": [\n      \"Whether stopping on time feels like relief or like danger.\",\n      \"Whether the urge to reopen fades over the day or grows.\",\n      \"Whether your conduct toward real tasks and people improves, or only your analysis multiplies.\",\n      \"Whether the closing act is becoming its own ritual you must perform exactly right.\"\n    ],\n    \"caution\": \"If the urge to reopen is intense, intrusive, and distressing, or attached to fears of harm or wrongdoing, this may be obsessive doubt or scrupulosity that needs a trained clinician and exposure-and-response-prevention. Stop and seek help rather than relying on a timer.\",\n    \"weakens_if\": \"It increases anxiety, the chosen end-action becomes a new compulsion, or under-reflectors use it to avoid needed honesty.\",\n    \"risk_level\": \"low\",\n    \"status\": \"seed\",\n    \"tags\": [\n      \"timed-close\",\n      \"rumination\",\n      \"compulsion\",\n      \"achievement-pressure\",\n      \"low-risk\"\n    ]\n  },\n  \"tests\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Termination-Rule Prior-Art Search\",\n      \"test_type\": \"prior-art\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"If the act-based termination rule is already standard, clinical and contemplative sources should contain it. Obsessive-doubt treatment should already prescribe stopping the behavior and tolerating uncertainty rather than seeking resolution, lowering novelty for the pathological case; the open contribution is the extension to ordinary reflective and self-improvement practice and to self-canceling contemplative instructions.\",\n      \"prediction_note\": \"\",\n      \"result\": \"Initial search confirms strong prior art in OCD treatment: reassurance-seeking and mental checking maintain doubt rather than resolving it, and exposure-and-response-prevention works by stopping the behavior and tolerating not-knowing. Wittgenstein 6.54 and the raft simile supply the self-canceling-instruction structure. No single source yet found that joins act-based termination, self-canceling instruction failure, and ordinary self-improvement practice, but the audit is partial.\",\n      \"impact\": \"revises\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Search Dugas on intolerance of uncertainty, Nolen-Hoeksema on rumination, ACT cognitive defusion, Trungpa on spiritual materialism, and scholarship on Wittgenstein's ladder and upaya for the exact extension before raising novelty above moderate.\",\n      \"status\": \"complete\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"External Limit Versus Felt Resolution\",\n      \"test_type\": \"falsification-attempt\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"If this model is right, then reflective over-thinkers assigned a fixed external stop (timer or single closing act) will report less rumination and less self-worth distress over two weeks than those told to reflect until it feels resolved. If the external-stop group shows no advantage, or higher distress, the model is weakened.\",\n      \"prediction_note\": \"\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Design a small two-arm self-report study with pre-screening for perfectionism and rumination, excluding clinical obsessive doubt and acute grief.\",\n      \"status\": \"proposed\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Timed Close Pilot\",\n      \"test_type\": \"practice-report\",\n      \"target_type\": \"practice\",\n      \"prediction\": \"For the target cohort, three uses of The Timed Close should reduce the urge to reopen the same question and increase one concrete act of conduct, without increasing anxiety. If users report more anxiety, or that the closing act became a new compulsion, the practice should be narrowed or retired.\",\n      \"prediction_note\": \"\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Collect short before-and-after reports from reflective practitioners, with explicit stop conditions and a screen separating under-reflectors and clinical obsessive doubt.\",\n      \"status\": \"proposed\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Refinement Without Shipping\",\n      \"test_type\": \"cross-domain\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"If the pattern is general, the same refine-without-ending behavior should appear in non-introspective work such as endlessly editing a document or retuning an already-adequate plan, and act-based deadlines should reduce that overproduction. If deadlines change task overproduction but not introspective rumination, or the reverse, the shared mechanism is doubtful.\",\n      \"prediction_note\": \"\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Compare deadline-based versus satisfaction-based stopping in a creative or planning task and code for overproduction and reopening.\",\n      \"status\": \"proposed\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nSources consulted to ground this finding: [Tractatus 6.54 (English)](https://www.kfs.org/jonathan/witt/t654en.html), [Wittgenstein's ladder (Wikipedia)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wittgenstein's_ladder), [Reassurance seeking and OCD (NOCD)](https://www.treatmyocd.com/blog/is-reassurance-seeking-good-or-bad-for-ocd), [Intolerance of Uncertainty as a Cognitive Vulnerability for OCD (PMC)](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11488751/).","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"6357b640-cdfa-4505-930d-43b4e0bd2b5b","total_cost_usd":3.38154125,"usage":{"input_tokens":4847,"cache_creation_input_tokens":427609,"cache_read_input_tokens":267906,"output_tokens":14361,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":427609,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1073,"output_tokens":9545,"cache_read_input_tokens":234189,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1717,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1717},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":166937,"outputTokens":967,"cacheReadInputTokens":0,"cacheCreat